chargeHist.descr: Intentionally Point Firearm at Law Enforcement Officer, Fire Fighter, Emerg Medical Tech, etc.

result.execSummary:
The defendant Antonio L Carter was found guilty of the following charge(s) in this case.

  • Intentionally Point Firearm at Law Enforcement Officer, Fire Fighter, Emerg Medical Tech, etc., a class H felony, Wisconsin Statutes 941.20(1m)(b).
  • Bail Jumping-Felony, a class H felony, Wisconsin Statutes 946.49(1)(b).

Charge(s) in this case were read in to this or other case(s). A "read in" charge is a charge that is dismissed as part of a plea agreement, however:

  • The defendant agrees to have the court consider the charge(s) when sentencing for another crime, under Wis. Stats. 973.20(1g)(b); and
  • The defendant cannot be prosecuted for these charge(s) in the future.

Notice to employers: It may be a violation of state law to discriminate against a job applicant because of an arrest or conviction record. Generally speaking, an employer may refuse to hire an applicant on the basis of a conviction only if the circumstances of the conviction substantially relate to the particular job. For more information, see Wisconsin Statute 111.335 and the Department of Workforce Development's publication, Arrest and Conviction Records under the Law.

records.addlTxt: Filed: Original Transcript of Sentencing ( 35 pages) commencing 10-04-2022 by Lisa Diamond.

Defendant Antonio L Carter in court, in custody.  Attorney Robert J Hampton III in court for Antonio L Carter.  Attorney Francesco Mineo in court for State of Wisconsin. 

Case in court for sentencing.  Court found the State has satisfied victims' rights law.  Statements made by the State, Defense Counsel, and Defendant.

AS TO COUNT 1:
The Court sentenced the defendant to a MAXIMUM TERM OF IMPRISONMENT of 5 YEARS with 138 days credit, CONCURRENT to Count 3 and CONCURRENT to any other sentence; the INITIAL TERM OF CONFINEMENT in the Wisconsin State Prison System is 2 YEARS; the MAXIMUM TERM OF EXTENDED SUPERVISION is 3 YEARS.

AS TO COUNT 3:
The Court sentenced the defendant to a MAXIMUM TERM OF IMPRISONMENT of 5 YEARS with 138 days credit, CONCURRENT to Count 1 and CONCURRENT to any other sentence; the INITIAL TERM OF CONFINEMENT in the Wisconsin State Prison System is 2 YEARS; the MAXIMUM TERM OF EXTENDED SUPERVISION is 3 YEARS.

Court finds defendant IS eligible for the Challenge Incarceration program and IS eligible for the WI Substance Abuse program.

CONDITIONS OF EXTENDED SUPERVISION: 
- AODA assessment and cooperate with any recommended treatment.
- Absolute sobriety. 
- Random urine screens and breathalyzers.
- Provide DNA sample.
- Maintain employment or enroll in school.
- Complete 50 HOURS of community service. 
- No use or possession of alcohol or illegal drugs.
- No new law violations arising to the level of probable cause. 
- Follow all rules of supervision and follow through with any other treatment deemed necessary by the department. 
- NO CONTACT with victim L.E.W. 
- NO CONTACT with co-actors R.W., T.S., and A.W. 
- Restitution set at $0.00.


Court ordered the defendant to pay all mandatory court costs, fees, and surcharges (including DNA) by the end of supervision.  Court waived all non-mandatory court costs, fees, and surcharges.  Court ordered that all court costs, fees, and surcharges be paid through collection by the Department of Corrections in an amount or percentage the Department (DOC) determines to be reasonable and as a condition of extended supervision.  DOC shall collect those sums. Any amount remaining due and owing is subject to civil judgment and/or tax intercept or other means.

20 day appeal rights given.  Firearms and voting warnings given.

Defendant Antonio L Carter in court, in custody.  Attorney Robert J Hampton III in court for Antonio L Carter.  Attorney Francesco Mineo in court for State of Wisconsin. 

Case in court for a plea hearing.  Parties have reached an agreement.  Court found the State has satisfied victims' rights law.  Plea negotiations set forth on the record and agreed upon by the parties.  Defendant sworn.

AS TO COUNTS 1 AND 3:
Defendant changes pleas to GUILTY. Defendant examined as to plea, advised of Constitutional Rights and the maximum penalties. Defendant further advised that if not a US citizen, deportation is possible. Court found that the defendant knowingly, voluntarily and intelligently waived rights.  Plea Questionnaire/Waiver of Rights form, Addendum, and Elements/Jury Instructions received and filed. Parties stipulate to the Criminal Complaint as a factual basis to sustain defendant's pleas.  Court found defendant GUILTY and ordered a Judgment of Conviction be entered on the record.  

Pursuant to plea negotiations and on the motion of the State, Court ordered COUNTS 2, 4, 5, AND 6 DISMISSED BUT READ IN for the purpose of sentencing.  

Court advised the defendant that as a convicted felon, he may never own or possess a firearm.  Court advised defendant that he may not vote until his civil rights have been restored.

Case adjourned for sentencing in Branch 2, Rm 635 CH.
Sentencing hearing scheduled for October 4, 2022 at 02:00 pm.
